title: Tribute to a 'Subber Code'
content:
For two weeks dow I'b had this code.
A subber code! It's bery bad.
A scratchy throat, a ruddy doze,
ed doebody seebs to udderstad
be wed I talk. I get doe sbiles or sybathy.
(A leper has bore freds thad be.)
By ears are stuvved, I hack ed wheeze,
I cough ed gasp, I sdiff ed sdeeze.
I'b purchased ebery rebedy
the drug stores sell - frob A to Z.
Aspirid. Codact. Sidu-tabs.
Bicks idhalers. Pills ed caps-
ules. Duthig works. Dot chicked soup,

Ed writig poebs is tough edough,
but try it wed your doze is stuvved!

ed there's just wud thig I wad to say:

title: Fatherhood's rewards; subtle, unending
content:
Sigmund Freud was overjoyed
when he tripped on the id and the ego.
But I was in heaven when my eldest turned seven
and we paddled down the Oswego.
Alfred Nobel was happy as hell
when he stumbled on T.N.T.
But I had more fun when my five-year-old son
played a toy drum recital for ME.
When Einstein declared E was m times c squared
he felt giddy and Truth-struck no doubt.
But my spirit soars up when I lift the oars up
and watch my two boys fish for trout.
Ted Turner turns gray and gets older each day
as he measures his wealth in Atlanta.
But I own a treasure that stops time forever:
the letters my sons sent to Santa.

Fame can be fickle. Ambition's a tickle
that can turn into terminal itch.
But thanks to my progeny, one thing is clear to me:
on Life's bottom line, I am rich!
signature:
(J.D. Evans, a pseudonym, is a South Jersey writer who yells at his sons
when their bedrooms are a mess ... occasionally.)

title: Happiness is warm Zapper
content:
I'd like to invent a pocket-sized Zapper
a portable, monogrammed laser-bushwacker.
A painless and bloodless device I could use
to "eliminate" (neatly) the people I choose.

-	Overweight drivers who swerve to the right
before they turn left I would Zap with delight.
-	People at movies who chatter out loud
I would Zap into atoms (if I were allowed.)
-	I'd Zap into vapors (if I had my way)
all the zombies who tell me to "have a nice day."
-	I'd Zap politicians and Howard Cosell,
and unfunny people with dumb jokes to tell.
-	I'd Zap lines at banks and toll booths, of course.
I'd Zap health food freaks without any remorse.
-	If I saw a car that was parked on TWO spaces,
I'd Zap car and driver. I wouldn't leave traces.

-	If I had a Zapper I'd happily smite
all the jerks who distract me when I try to write.
But one thought has soured this sweet fantasy:
suppose other people had Zappers like me,
and one of them wanted to Zap and disperse
anonymous authors of jangling verse ...

Back to the drawing boards! Now I think twice,
I'll develop an anti-Zap-Zapping device.
signature:
(J.D. Evans, a pseudonym, is a South Jersey writer who makes left turns
after switching on his right directional signal ... occasionally.)

title: Making a deal is no deal at all
content:
At times I suspect
I'm the only one left
who buys things without making deals.
No "friends in the trade"
or swaps to be made,
no buddies with "bargains" and "steals."

No discounts from in-laws
(or friends who have in-laws)
no neighbors to cut me a break.
I pay sticker price
and never think twice
about cost-cutting steps I could take


Like calling a "friend"
(of a "friend" I dislike)
and chatting along casually,
before asking this "friend"
(of a "friend" I dislike)
to do a small favor for me.

I'd save a few bucks
and then I could cluck
how I get things for nothing or free.
(But then I might get
people I've never met
calling up asking favors of me.)
Hmmmmmmm.
Now I reflect
I suppose it's correct
that I never transact under counters.
With no IOUs
I have nothing to lose
to "friends" who are friendship discounters.
signature:
(J.D. Evans, a pseudonym, is a New Jersey writer who looks for ads that
say "Half Price for Poets" É occasionally.)

title: It was future shock (chimpanzee-style)
content:
News item: Ham, the first chimpanzee to ride a
rocket into space, has died at the age of 26. Ham
rode a Redstone rocket into a sub-orbital flight on
Jan. 3l, l96l. He died at a North Carolina zoological
park where he had lived for 2 1/2 years.


He was never the same when he came back from space.
He seemed awkward. Uneasy. Alone. Out of place.
He'd sit in his cage with a strange, dreamy stare,
a smug sort of look for a "dumb" chimp to wear.

He wouldn't play games with his simian brothers
("Hide Your Ears" "Chase Your Tail" and all of the others.)
He would sit there for hours, alone and content,
gazing endlessly out at the vast firmament.

His trip to the ozone had changed Ham inside.
It was more than a journey, much more than a ride.
He had seen the earth curve, seen mountains and seas,
he had swung toward the sun on a cosmic trapeze.

From the earth to the stars in a single lifetime,
while thousands of species still crawled through the slime.
Darwin was right; Ham became a believer.
Zoologically speaking, he was an overachiever.

He never fit in when he came back to earth.
His brief rocket flight was a strange second birth.
Trapped on a ladder between monkey and man:
A small step for NASA, a big leap for Ham.

The kids who stopped by to see Ham at the zoo
weren't really impressed, but then they never knew
all the dizzying thoughts that would race through his brain.
Poor Ham just sat there. He couldn't explain.

I like to think that the zoo's personnel
who were sent in to clean out poor Ham's little cell
swept out so quickly they just didn't see
Ham's scrawl in the dust: E=MC ...
signature:
(J.D. Evans, a pseudonym, is a New Jersey writer who hums "Thus Spake
Zarathustra" to himself ... occasionally.)

title: Honesty Day - when you care enough to send your very worst
content:
The calendar's loaded with "nice" holidays,
occasions for presents, for flowers and praise.
There are dozens of days made for syrupy gushers,
occasions for unblushing kissers andhuggers:
-	a day just for fathers, a day just for mothers,
-	a day just for in-laws, a day just for lovers.
What's missing, however, I think you'll agree
is a day to be NASTY - anonymously.


Imagine how great we would all feel inside
if we could release all the feelings we hide
about bosses, employees, "friends" and relations.
A day to be candid without trepidations!

To the lazy employee who dogs it all day,
a card that says "Why don't you try earning part of your pay?"

For the clown at the office who offers dumb tips,
some tape and instructions for sealing his lips.
For the boss who wants more work than he ever gives,
an X-rated card filled with choice expletives.

Just think of the cards you could send on that day,
and the long-suppressed things you could finally say:
"You're a bore." "You're a jerk." "You're a grouch." "You're a clod."
"You're a miser, a goof-off, an air-head, a snob."

Hallmark would love it! The gift shops would, too.
"Honesty Day." I've thought it all through.
The symbol? Don Rickles, an overweight cupid
throwing darts at the grumpy, the dull and the stupid.

On the 15th of April (when taxes are due)
send "Truth Cards" to people who irritate you.
Be candid, be honest, be frank and be curt,
but don't sign the cards.You could really get hurt!
signature:
(J.D. Evans, a pseudonym, is a New Jersey writer who feels hypocritical
when he sends greeting cards ... occasionally.)

title: A fatherly chat about sex
content:
We kept sex a secret (as good parents must)
saying nothing at all about passion or lust.
We carefully checked all the films he would see,
restricting the spectrum to G and PG.
My handful of copies of Playboy and Oui
were locked in a briefcase (and I kept the key.)
In short, we allowed him to make it to ten
without broaching the subject of women and men.


But boys after all will be boys at their school
and at ten, boys are eager to act tough and cool.
And the X-rated words he brought home said to me:
"It's time for THAT talk." My wife said that she
didn't think it was her job: "I'll laugh and I'll blush."
I said that I'd do it. "Not yet.There's no rush."

I carefully thought of the things that I'd say,
determined to put it in a pure, wholesome way.
No crudeness, no dull list of clinical words,
no sexist stuff either, no "bees and the birds."
An open discussion. Just father and son.
The moment arrived.We were watching "Shogun."

"Um, what do you know about, ah, sex?" I inquired
as we watched a young woman that Blackthorn desired
slowly undress on our color TV.
"What?" my son asked. "Are you talking to me?"
"Sex," I repeated, clearing my throat.
"Do you have any questions, however remote?"
He did, so we started and stumbled along.
He had some things right, but some basic things wrong.

I straightened him out, and did it quite neatly.
But it all didn't go as I planned. Not completely.
The response that I hoped for was a trifle grandiose.
He didn't say: "Ah!" What he said was: "Oh, gross!"
signature:
(J.D. Evans, a pseudonym, is a New Jersey writer who wonders what it's
like to be a bachelor ... occasionally.)

title: Some have a closer walk with God
content:
"On matters theological
it's hard to be logical
if you don't belong to my church.

"My faith has God's ear.
You can argue all year,
but I've checked it. I've done my research.

"Oh, I'm sure you believe
that your prayers receive
undivided attention from Him.

"But that's an illusion,
a faulty conclusion.
Faith-Wise you're out on a limb.


"He listens to me,
and someday you'll see
that your prayers are virtually useless.

"What? I heard that crack.
You jerk! Take it back
or I'll leave your mouth bloody and toothless.

"That's a lie! An insult!
My faith's not a cult.
We worship the way He intended.

"What we do is a joke?
It's all mirrors and smoke?
That's it. Our friendship's suspended.

"I hate heathens like you
who just misconstrue
The Truth and leave it diminished.

"But God's on my side,
and I'll prove it 'outside'
when this moment of silence is finished."
signature:
(J.D. Evans, a pseudonym, is a New Jersey writer who thinks about the
consequences of prayer in the schools ... occasionally.)

title: he world's not a stage, just a TV set
content:
On As The World Turns, Karen's help has been spurned
(it's Karen who's blackmailing James).
Dee's out of jail (I think she made bail)
and Ariel's still playing games.

On One Life to Live, poor Bo's parentage
is a secret to no one but Bo.
Katrina's arrested, and the nurse has accepted
a date with 'ol Drew (ho, ho, ho!).


Suzanne (Guiding Light) is still out of sight
thanks to Tony who keeps her in hiding.
Rebecca and Quint are still wearing splints
from the car crash they had while out riding.

On Search for Tomorrow Keith has to borrow
some money, and Andie's a mean little brat.
Kristen miscarried and Suzi got married.
And Travis said he smelled a rat.

Ian (Edge of Night) is doing all right
after he rescued Raven from Snell.
Nicole may have lied about why Nora died.
(I think that Sid knows but won't tell.)

Capitol's Sam is still in a jam.
and Paula's dark secret's still safe.
Lizbeth loves Jordy (and that really floored me,
she seemed like a sweet little waif.)

Reagan's in trouble (the polls popped his bubble),
Afghanistan's still occupied.
And Begin supports Sharon (though the courts
put some blame for Beirut on his side).

Mike Matthews was missing while a blizzard was blitzing
South Jersey. And Reese Palley's yacht
isn't hooked to Ma Bell so no one can tell
if his trip was "convenient" or not.

Fact or fiction, who cares? High intrigue? Low affairs?
They're distractions, they help us to cope
with the days of our lives, our dull 9-to-5s.
Pick a channel, all of life is a soap.
signature:
(J.D. Evans, a pseudonym, is a New Jersey writer who thinks it will all
end happily ... occasionally.)

title: Undrstnclng stck lstngs is hzrdous to yr hlth
content:
Wlsn Brn (that's Wilson Brown)
came down with a fatal disease.
Blame it all on Dow Jones and the stock Wilson owned,
he lost his i's, a's, o's and e's.

Each day he would scan the listings that ran
on the newspaper's stock market page.
Inserting dropped vowels with frustrated scowls,
decoding the New York exchange.

At first it was tough to decipher the stuff
that appeared in the smallest of print.
But at last Brown was able to zip through the tables,
with hardly a frown or a squint.

SoRoy and WashGs he'd decode in a flash
then ponder a more cryptic name,
like TxPac or WmDx, StPacCp or Timpix.
But the effort soon scrambled his brain.

Misnin? OvrhDr? UslfeFd and RalsPur?
He'd ponder the hard ones for days.
He'd talk to himself: "BIkHPw? KaPL pf?"
while his eyes grew weary and glazed.

The obsession set in, and Brown would begin
to speak in a strange dialect.
There were words he'd condense that he thought made more sense
in a form that was brief and direct.

"Gd mrning!" he'd say to his wife every day.
"Wht's for brkfst?" he'd say to his son.
All the stenos at work thought old Brown was a jerk,
and his memos confused everyone.

"We bttr nt buy cncrte blcks frm ths guy,"
Brown's boss heard him firmly insist.


"His cmpny's blcks are made frm crshd rcks,
and wht's wrse, he's chrging us list!"

Brown lost his friends and his job in the end,
a victim of stock marketese.
He went on the skids, lost his wife and his kids,
died waiting in line for some cheese.

So if you invest, might I humbly suggest
that those listings you simply ignore.
They'll just drive you crazy like Brown, so be lazy.
Going nuts is what brokers are for.

title: Harbingers of spring: Nature's page one story
content:
A leafy "thing" erupted in my front yard overnight.
A crocus maybe. (I can't tell.) But what a longed-for sight.
The earth is still a-ticking to a rhythm all its own:
the constant and determined beat of Nature's metronome.
It hasn't paused a "tick" for you, nor held a "tock" for me;
it hasn't been distracted from its endless symphony.
It doesn't care if Beirut falls or if a premier dies.
What mankind finds "important" it has yet to recognize.
My morning paper missed the news. It wasn't on Page 1.
It glimmered green and silent in the brilliant morning sun.
A banner headline might have said: Spring? Early Overtures.
The story needed just one line: "The universe endures."
signature:
(J.D. Evans, a pseudonym, is a New Jersey writer who does public
relations work for Mother Nature, Inc  occasionally.)

title: Portraits of professionals
content:
CCOUNTANTS find loopholes where none should exist
and balance your books with a twist of the wrist.
For a fee they can help you to stay out of debt
(and that fee's deductible, let's not forget!).


Accountants exempt you from taxes and bills,
and help spend your fair share of trust funds and wills.
Their hands as they figure are dizzying blurs
(as long as the money they handle's not theirs.)


UREAUCRATS are terrible beasts,
they sneer the most and care the least.
They're callous, heartless, rude, unkind,
and love to make you wait in line.
They're mean and lazy like crocodiles
and - like the crocs - wear phony smiles.
Crossing a sloth and a vampire-bat,
God created the Bureaucrat.


HIROPRACTORS mangle bones
and never mind their patients' groans.
They pull and twist and stretch and crack
stiff legs and arms and fronts an backs.
They pound and punch and squeeze and slap
to make joints pop and muscles snap.
They're just like wrestlers you see on TV,
but one thing's missing: a referee.


ENTISTS are thankful the mouth was invented.
It keeps their wives happy, their children contented.
But working on mouths can be hard on the nerves
of a Dentist as well as the patients he serves.
When your Dentist seems nervous or worried and glum
(when he's drilling your teeth or cleaning your gums),
put yourself in his shoes. Go ahead.Visualize
all those fear-stricken faces staring straight in your eyes.
signature:
(J.D. Evans, a pseudonym, is a New Jersey writer who wonders about
other careers ... occasionally.)

title: Let's try happy news for rose-hued views
content:
"TV should report good news." - Ronald Reagan

I can see it all now, through a haze, like a dream:
THE HAPPY NEWS HOUR! A marvelous scheme.
No grim, ugly photos of war in Iraq,
or film of a blood-thirsty, crazed maniac.
No talk of Dioxin and hazardous wastes,
or stories of aspirin that's cyanide-laced.
Sanitized news! An overdue notion.
A tonic for grimness; a cheerfulness potion.

Who wants to watch all that bleak, dismal news?
It just makes us sad, or gets us confused.
Recession, depression, war and disease;
hungry Americans waiting for cheese;
EPA scandals, cops on the take;
volcanoes erupting; blizzards and quakes.
Day after day, it's a sobering diet.
THE HAPPY NEWS HOUR.Why don't we try it?

We'd have White House reports that never allude
to cost overruns or political feuds,
and charming accounts from Russia and Cuba
of comrades who play balalaikas and tubas.
"Accu-nice" forecasts that call for clear skies
(and ignore any trouble ahead, weather-wise.)
A rose-colored view of the world's what we're after:
a portrait of life to provoke smiles and laughter.

What you don't know can't hurt you - that's what they say -
so a HAPPY NEWS HOUR might help us to stay
confident, cheerful, secure and content
(if Rather and Brokaw and Koppel consent.)
And if Reagan is right, the ratings would soar.
Let's start it next year. 1984.
signature:
(J.D. Evans, a pseudonym, is a New Jersey writer who thinks about
nattering nabobs of negativity É occasionally.)

title: Old mob wouldn't relish 'weiner wars'
content:
News item: N.J. State Police are investigating
possible mob influence in Atlantic City's hot dog
vending business.

"Scarface" Capone would shudder and groan
if he knew what they'd done to his mob.
He'd be angry and flustered: "Selling hot dogs and mustard?
That ain't no crime, that's a job!

"Numbers and rackets, and silk, pinstriped jackets:
that's real work and real mobster clothes.
Any gangster who peddles weiners and pretzels
should be beat with a bat or a hose!

"Booze, drugs, and broads. Scams, heists and frauds.
That kind of stuff we do good.
But muscling guys who sell hot dogs ain't wise.
Franks ain't a vice, it's a food.

"Hot dogs? Forget it.You guys'll regret it.
They'll bust you tomorrow or sooner.
When you mess with folks' lunch, you get troubles - a bunch.
And a quick, one-way trip to La Tuna."
signature:
(J.D. Evans, a pseudonym, is a New Jersey writer who thinks about the
deterioration of professional images É occasionally.)

title: More beastly careers to avoid (if you can)
content:
A contemporary bestiary: Part 2



DITORS wrestle with syntax and grammar
and love to make young writers stutter and stammer.
They're paid to find fault, delete and revise;
spot fragments, misspellings, cross T's and dot I's.
If God had employed one of them up in heaven
He'd get back His tablets marked: "Trim it to 7."


ITNESS INSTRUCTORS are cheerful and lean
but deep in their hearts they are nasty and mean.
They torture poor souls who appear overweight
and make them regret all the junk food they ate.
They drive them and push them: "Let's go! Exercise!"
They're monsters in Danskins; de Sades in disguise.


AMBLERS are funny who dress like Wayne Newton.
(They look like an army ol' Wayne's been recruiting.)
Their shirts are all open, three buttons at least;
they wear their wives' jewelery, their limos are leased.
They talk like high rollers, they tip like them, too,
but at work the next week, they bum spare change from you.


OOKERS are ladies with meters for hearts.
They have little ambition and even less smarts.
They work at odd hours (odd angles as well)
and slowly wear out the one product they sell.
Time is their foreman, age is their boss;
the face in the mirror keeps track of the cost.
signature:
(J.D. Evans, a pseudonym, is a New Jersey writer who writes about
careers ... occasionally.)

title: In the spring a poet's fancy turns to work
content:
Spring is sprung! Hurrah! Hooray!
I couldn't take another day
of Winter's cold or Winter's snow.
(I'd make a lousy Eskimo.)

No clunky boots! No heavy coats!
No kids with colds and scratchy throats!
No ice-cold sheets upon my bed,
no heating bills to read with dread!

Spring! Hurrah! Spring! Hooroo!
Right on schedule: overdue.
Now where'd I put the fishing gear
that got all tangled up last year ...

Start the mower? Get the rake?
It's time to get the yard in shape?
Wash the windows? Now? Today?
Put the sleds and skis away?
Patch the screens? Fix the gate?
Little League practice? Dinner's late?
A vegetable garden? Chop down trees?
I want a hammock, not carrots and peas!
I'll take all the animals down to the vet's,
just let me go jogging before the sun sets!
You used my old sweatsuit for polishing cloths?
They're charging us what just to spray gypsy moths?

Aaaaaaaaa!

Winter is grim, but Spring is a bummer.
I wish it was June. I wish it was Summer.
signature:
(J.D. Evans, a pseudonym, is a New Jersey writer who thinks about Tahiti
... occasionally.)

title: he joy of "shing: is it for reel?
content:
Fishing is pointless, the cynics agree:
"It's a sport with no danger and no referee.
No fans on the sidelines (no sidelines, in fact.)
Feeding worms to a fish? There's no 'sport' in that!

"No field goals, no fast breaks, no crisp double plays;
no Phillie Phanatics, no instant replays.
No game plans, no coaches, no sweat and no strain;
no bone-wrenching contact, no blood and no pain.

"It's quiet - like knitting - no boos and no cheers,
no vendors with hot dogs and neat souvenirs.
It's boring and silly. It isn't a sport.
It's a dull waste of time," the cynics all snort.

The cynics are right, we anglers agree,
as we patiently cast in the lakes and the sea,
looking for "keepers" that might not be there;
sitting in silence, breathing clean air;
far from the crowds and competitive urges,
wasting our time luring basses and perches.
Pity us anglers (pathetic, sad drips)
as we wade in cold water that's up to our hips.
Fussing with spinners and leaders and plugs,
sloshing through mud and fighting off bugs.
We anglers are tragic and hopeless, no doubt.
We sit there and dream about landing huge trout
while we study the water for vague, subtle signs.
But it's we who are hooked at the ends of our lines.
signature:
(J.D. Evans, a pseudonym, is a New Jersey writer who talks to himself
while fishing ... occasionally.)

title: A plea to lawmakers: Post no (dumb) bills
content:
Each year the Assembly and Senate debate
some remarkable notions of laws for our state.
Your state legislature is serious, folks.
These bills are pending.They're real.They're not jokes.

There's a bill in the hopper that makes it a crime
to cross someone's lawn when delivering wine.
Another that's waiting (and might make the grade)
gives judges permission to march in parades.

If one bill's adopted you wouldn't pay taxes
on a "recycled pillow" or "recycled mattress."
There's a bill in committee that strikes me as cruel.
It would keep ice cream vendors away from a school.

A bill that will probably make mobsters depressed
would require a permit for bulletproof vests.
Another proposal would not let us see
any X-rated movies on cable TV.

A license to marry would cost lovers more
if S-1521 is approved on the floor.
There are licensing bills aimed at bikes and at boats,
and a bill that would regulate sellers of goats.

Too many laws and needless restrictions
let Freedom and Justice become contradictions.
Those who make laws should earn our respect:
it's the least that we ask, the least we expect.
How can we hold our lawmakers in awe
when they're telling us jokes and calling it Law?
signature:
(J.D. Evans, a pseudonym, is a New Jersey writer who reads the New
Jersey Legislative Index ... occasionally.)

title: If no news is good news, it's bad news all around
content:
Hardly a day of the week seems to pass
that doesn't find someone outraged and aghast
over something that ran on page one, six or 30
that "proves" that the press is unfair and dirty.

Political types are chronic complainers,
(so are some athletes and some entertainers).
If a story says nice things they don't seem to mind,
but an unpleasant truth that's in print? That's a crime!

"Why did you print that?" they bellow and shout.
"It's a scheme to destroy me!" They haven't a doubt
that the press is a person who's not on their side,
a person who's nasty and vicious and snide.
The fact that the facts that appeared were all true
is ignored as they holler and threaten to sue.
The problem goes deeper than names in the news,
there are readers who hate facts that challenge their views.

If the press runs a story (an honest account)
on any great issue, some readers will pounce
crying "Bias!" "Distortion!" "Fraud!" and "All lies!"
(And sometimes the shouts seem to come from both sides.)

The problem is ancient; it's not really new.
What's good news for me may be bad news for you.
The poor sap dispatched with grim facts for a king
had his head chopped. Some critics would do the same thing
to honest reporters with no axe to grind
who are damned for disclosing the facts that they find.

"You can't change the facts," good newsmen declare
when their critics accuse them of not being fair.
Is news ever "fair?" I suppose it depends
on whether the facts hurt your foes or your friends.
signature:
(J.D. Evans, a pseudonym, is a New Jersey writer who gets into
arguments about the news business at cocktail parties ... occasionally.)

title: 'M' is for the million cards you've bought her
content:
This one's for mom whose day today is.
Your moms and mine, my wife's and my kids'.
Moms who are fat, moms who are trim,
moms who are sloppy, moms who are prim;
moms who play tennis, moms who have jobs,
moms who are friendly, moms who are snobs.

Why do we hunt through the cards on the rack
searching for One Card we wouldn't put back?
The Mothers' Day. card that we'd swear was designed
in every respect with our mom in mind.
A verse that's not sloppy or dopey or dumb,
that has the right nickname: 'Mom,' 'Mommy' or 'Mum.'
A drawing our mom would choose for herself
to put on a wall or sit on a shelf.

It's not there of course, so we take second-best:
some satiny thing not as bad as the rest.
"The thought is what counts," we say with a mutter,
then dutifully sign it and send it to mother.

Know what I think? (Boy, Hallmark will hate this.)
All mass-produced cards are basically tasteless.
My mom's not your mom, and your mom's not mine,
moms don't roll off some assembly line.
Each mother is different, unique (just like you).
If you're sending a card then the least you should do
is make it yourself - like you did in third grade:
clumsy and crude, but lovingly made.
Draw lots of flowers and rainbows and hearts,
and write your own verse. Show mom your smarts.
What would it cost you? An hour? Maybe less.
Next year forget Hallmark. Send your mom your best.
signature:
(J.D. Evans, a pseudonym, is a New Jersey writer who picks wildflower
bouquets ... occasionally.)

title: Sky full of wonders, he wonders where
content:
I stood in the street in my unstockinged feet
staring up at a star-studded sky,
scouring the heavens (just me, J.D. Evans)
for the comet they said would pass by.

I remembered Kohoutek, but said "What the heck,
this time might be different.We'll see."
All I saw were some jets and the trees' silhouettes,
and some neighbors who peered out at me.

I was cold, bored and sore. I was no longer sure
why I stood there, straining my neck.
A police car stopped by, and an unsmiling guy
asked to see some ID for a check.

"A comet," I said. "With a tail and a head,
I've been looking but can't find it yet."
"The comet! That's right!" he said with delight,
and my vigil became a duet.

We stood side by side, and agreed to divide
the cosmos in two. Equally.
But when Bill Maclntyre came out to inquire
we divided the skies into threes.

Dogs barked in the night, folks turned on their lights,
and neighbors came out in their slippers.
The street was soon crowded, and two people shouted:
"I see it!" "Naah, that's the Big Dipper!"


Some cars driving by screeched off to the side.
"What happened?" the drivers all yelled.
"A murder? A riot?" The cop said "Be quiet!"
The size of the star party swelled.

Some six-packs appeared, and everyone cheered
when a low-flying airplane flew by.
The subs finally came, and I didn't complain
(though I'd ordered a corned beef on rye).

When the sky got all cloudy, the party turned rowdy,
and people were glaring at me.
"A comet?" "Says who?" I discreetly withdrew,
and abandoned that strange jamboree.

Hours went past until (finally) the last
of the seekers went home to his bed.
The comet? Who knows? It was there, I suppose.
That's what the astronomers said.

I've taken a vow: I never (nohow)
will ever look up at the sky.
And I know where I'll be - watching color TV -
when the comet called Halley's flies by.
signature:
(J.D. Evans, a pseudonym, is a New Jersey writer who reads "South
Jersey Skies" ... occasionally.)

title: Stopping by ski lodge on a frigid afternoon
content:
Whose skis are these? I think I know.
They should be on the chairlift, though,
or schussing down some icy trail
as falling rain turns into hail.
They should be whooshing down the hill
as wind turns skin to senseless leather.
It's only ten below - with wind-chill.
Perfect downhill skiing weather.
So where's my gang, the Alpine aces?
Scaling some storm-shrouded peak?

No.They're where they've been all week:
Inside. By roaring fireplaces.

Gee, it sure looks warm in there
But I must go and catch a chair,
and bite my tongue so I don't swear:
"All-day rentals? Not next $#!% year!"
signature:
(J.D. Evans, a pseudonym, is a New Jersey writer who finds someone to
talk to on a chairlift ... occasionally.)

title: he sands of time trickle relentlessly
content:
Tick. (Plastic rattles with funny clown faces.)
Tick. (Hide-and-seek games and piggy-back races.)
Tick. (Clumsy towers of alphabet blocks.)
Tick. (Tiny sneakers and Superman socks.)
Tick. (Kindergarten.) Tick. (A class play.)
Tick. It keeps ticking ... ticking away.

Tick. (Dental braces.) Tick. (Cub Scout hikes.)
Tick. (Music lessons.) Tick. (10-speed bikes.)
Tick. (Going fishing.) Tick. (Playing ball.)
Tick. (Spring.) Tick. (Winter.) Tick. (Summer.) Tick. (Fall.)
Tick. (Things to show him.) Tick. (Things to say.)
Tick. It keeps ticking ... ticking away.

Tick. (High school freshman.) Tick. (The first date.)
Tick. ("Don't wait up. Mom. I'll probably be late.")
Tick. (An old Chevy.) Tick. (Graduation.)
Tick. (A degree or a new occupation.)
Tick. (He's engaged.) Tick. (He's the groom.)
Tick. (A long look at his small, silent room.)

Time's not a villain,Time's not a thief.
Time's a Bag Lady with gaps in her teeth.
She prowls through our lives all night and all day,
collecting the minutes that we toss away.
Black holes in space? They're a small mystery
compared to the question that mystifies me.
Einstein - who juggled the stars in his brain -
was stumped for an answer. He couldn't explain:
"How did Tomorrow become a Today?"
Tick. It keeps ticking ... ticking away.
signature:
(J.D. Evans, a pseudonym, is a New Jersey writer who makes promises to
spend more time with his sons É occasionally.)

title: Barbecue feasts bring out the beast
content:
We slogged through the slime and ducked brontosauruses,
learned to start fires and grunted in choruses,
moved out of caves and learned how to read:
homo erectus, a marvelous breed.

We climbed Nature's ladder and learned to stand straight.
We learned to invent and we learned to create.
Airplanes, computers and satellite lasers,
self-cleaning ovens, disposable razors.

Civilized. Cultured. Literate. Neat.
We're no longer beasts. Look how calmly we eat.
Except when it's warm and The Caveman breaks through,
The Caveman within us who screams: "Barbecue!"

He dumps in the coals, he fumbles with fire,
and grins as the flames leap higher and higher.
He pours on some fluid that stinks up the air:
eau de Sunoco, the smell's everywhere.

His eyes fill with smoke, he presses ahead.
The chief does not rest till the whole tribe is fed.
For hours he grills. He sears and he fries,
turning food into things you cannot recognize.
Charcoal-black burgers as thick as a sponge.
Hot dogs so dry that they stick to your tongue.
Overcooked chicken coated with goo
(it's his "special sauce" but it tastes just like glue.)


No one enjoys it, but no one complains.
A cookout strikes deep, secret chords in our brains.
It stirs ancient memories of primeval days
before there were kitchens, before microwaves.
Back when we gnawed on the branches for brunch
and cannibals nibbled on us for their lunch.

Before there were blenders, before there were stoves.
Before there were bakers to bake bread in loaves.
Before there were knives with unbreakable handles.
Before there were napkins and elegant candles.
Before there were ice cubes and cocktails to nurse.
The hot dogs are burnt? Hey.Things could be worse!
signature:
(J.D. Evans, a pseudonym, is a New Jersey writer who subjects his family
to barbecues ... occasionally.)

title: Deck the halls with boughs of ... frustration
content:
This is the season of ancient chores,
of family customs, timeless rites.
Last week was Making Christmas Lists.
Today's the day we Hang The Lights.

The cardboard boxes stored away
where spiders wait in crawl-space caves
must be exhumed. It falls to me
to raise them from their musty graves.

The strings of lights I neatly packed
long months ago in separate sets
now prove to be a mass of knots:
a writhing, wormlike, tangled mess.

Un-weaving done, I plug them in.
They fail, of course.The age-old quirk:
A string of lights must always have
at least one bulb that does not work.

Light-by-light, I take them out.
Each bulb and socket's closely checked.
(The faulty bulb will never be
the very first one I inspect.)

All systems Go, I press ahead.
Collecting tools, I march outside.
As I hang lights, my two sons watch:
tough critics, never satisfied:

"Too many whites." "I hate the green."
"I think we ought to get some more."
"You need more blues." "Too few up top."
"It's too much like the house next door!"


At last it's done.The switch is thrown.
A hundred lights turn night to day.
The critics' verdicts? Unimpressed.
"It's not too bad." "It looks OK."

In years to come, when they're both men
with families of their own to raise,
I hope my sons will re-enact
the customs of our holidays.

If life is just, if life is fair,
I'll get to watch THEM Hang The Lights
and get to hear THEIR children say:
"Too many blues.You need more whites!"
signature:
(J.D. Evans, a pseudonym, is a New Jersey writer who mutters
"Humbug!" while balancing on ladders ... occasionally.)

title: Not all queens created regal(ly)
content:
There she goes, Miss Whatserstate.
In the race of the queens she was left at the gate.
A face in the crowd, she was upstaged all week
by more quotable hopefuls, by better physiques.

Her smile was OK, and her gown wasn't frowsy,
her swimsuit was modest, her act wasn't lousy.
She didn't play banjo or sing a capella;
she didn't dance "Swan Lake" or a wild tarantella.
She didn't twirl eggplants or juggle things spritely.
What she did was just ... dull.To put it politely.

When photographers snapped, she was just out of range;
when reporters showed up, she had just gone to change.
She liked Mr. Reagan and stay-at-home mothers;
she was cute, she was sweet, (like 49 others.)
She didn't make waves or cause a commotion,
but her makeup was special: Anonymous Lotion.

She was here but she wasn't, if you know what I mean:
A lady in waiting disguised as a queen.
Winning's not everything they taught her in school.
And guess who had Whatserstate in the $10 pool.
signature:
(J.D. Evans, a pseudonym, is a South Jersey writer who picks a winner ...
occasionally.)

title: Clipping coupons: unkindest of cuts?
content:
Rise up, you coupon clippers!
Let's end the coupon game
that keeps us all a-clipping
for discounts we can claim.

The corporate gnomes all giggle
as they watch us cut and clip,
collecting cents-off coupons
for our weekly shopping trip.

"A nickle off on Bounty!"
"A quarter off on Tide!"
We clip, and clip and clip them
and we set them all aside.

We hoard them all like misers.
Our thrift turns into greed.
We start collecting coupons
good for products we don't need!

We slash the daily papers,
we shred our magazines,
hunting coupons, coupons, coupons,
with a passion rarely seen.

On shopping day it's combat.
We storm the grocery aisles
snatching product-coupon "matches"
like consumer crocodiles.

And is our effort worth it?
Is our thriftiness admired?
"I'm sorry, sir," the cashier whines,
"this coupon has expired."
signature:
(J.D. Evans, a pseudonym, is a New Jersey writer who goes food
shopping É occasionally.)

title: Twinkle, twinkle liflle star, 'Mr. C' knows why you are
content:
News item: STOCKHOLM, Sweden - The Royal
Swedish Academy of Sciences announced Wednesday
that professor Subrahmanyan Chandrasekhar of the
University of Chicago won a Nobel Prize in physics
for his work on the evolution of stars.

Subrahmanyan Chandrasekhar
has cause to thank his lucky star.
It brought him glory, brought him fame,
for theories complex as his name.
Thanks to Mr. Chandrasekhar
we need not wonder what stars are.
But even brilliant Mr. C.
cannot resolve one mystery:
Can they print a name that size
on one small, golden, Nobel prize?
signature:
(J.D. Evans, a pseudonym, is a New Jersey writer who appreciates the
value of pseudonyms É occasionally.)

title: You say Gre-nay-da, I say Gra-nah-da;
content:
let's call this whole thing off











It was the very model of a problem territorial:
how to rid a nation of a leader dictatorial
without inviting protests and unceasing editorials
or U.N. resolutions that are bitterly censorial.
The President paraded all his talents elocutional,
his statements and his logic were at best circumlocutional.
In Congress, there were arguments on powers institutional,
and someone even whispered: "Is invasion Constitutional?"

A landing force was organized and labeled "international."
The President insisted that his actions were quite rational:
"Our interests in that region are indubitably national.
We have a sacred duty to stop thugs who are irrational."
Our allies were appalled, and said invasion was not sensible.
A score of Latin nations found our conduct reprehensible.
We fought a comic-opera war and said without hypocrisy:
"Perhaps we acted crudely, but we did it for democracy."

But one small question, please, to be put before the President:
Does our Grenada action set a military precedent?
Will Moscow now be tossing us a wink conspiratorial
for using their techniques to handle problems territorial?
signature:
(J.D. Evans, a pseudonym, is a New Jersey writer who remembers
Afghanistan, Hungary and Czechoslovakia É occasionally.)

title: A campaign dictionary for voters
content:
Thoughts on political advertising:

Candidates are not like us.
Their language is ... unique.
That's why I keep this glossary
to decode campaign-speak.

EXPERIENCED!

Although incumbents like this word
it must be emphasized,
it merely means they won last time.
(And, boy, were they surprised!)

HARD-WORKING!

People who dabble in politics
(because they're bored or rich)
will use this word to justify
their sudden, civic itch.

DEDICATED!

You guessed it.These are candidates
with rotten kids or spouses.
They run each year for office
to escape unhappy houses.






TRUSTWORTHY!

This does not mean "I'm honest"
as you more than likely thought.
It means: "I may have sinned a bit,
but I was never caught."

COMPASSIONATE!

He helps the poor and powerless.
His zeal is laudatory.
Alas, he'll only help them
if the press will run a story;

KNOWLEDGEABLE!

He knows which backs need scratching
and which reports to leak.
And (unlike his opponent)
he knows when not to speak.

CONCERNED!

He listens so intently.
The image is perfected.
But what concerns him most of all
is getting re-elected.
signature:
(J.D. Evans, a pseudonym, is a New Jersey writer who votes for
candidates despite their advertising claims ... occasionally.)

title: Modern family life: meeting on the run
content:
These days we touch through messages
Scotch-taped to doors and clocks:
"The cats weren't fed." "Pick up some bread."
"Dear Mom: I'm out of socks!"
The pace at times is frantic.
It's like Grand Central Station.
Our movements are a symphony:
The Family Orchestration.

Alarm clocks sound at intervals,
we go four separate ways.
"Piano practice after school."
"We're out of mayonnaise."
We eat four separate lunches,
four separate breakfasts, too.
We meet (sometimes) at supper
and we ask: "What's new with you?"
There's nothing we can do, of course,
to change our family's ways.
We're trapped by circumstances.
We're like gerbils in a maze.

Last night I had a nightmare
that made me toss and sweat:
I was captured by guerrillas
in the mountains of Tibet.
Before I finally got away
a year or more had passed.
I walked and swam and hitch-hiked
till I got back home, at last.
"I'm here! I'm free!" I shouted.
What I found just made me sad.
A note was on the freezer door:
"Has anyone seen Dad?"
signature:
(J.D. Evans, a pseudonym, is a New Jersey writer who remembers what
his wife and children look like ... occasionally.)

title: School wasn't 'cool' in not-too-distant past
content:
Thoughts while visiting a third-grade class on
Parents' Day:

Sister Francis would deplore
that bright red carpet on - the floor.
Nor would she be amused by all
those posters hanging on the wall:
"School Is Cool!" and "Reading's Nifty!"
(School was grim in 1950.)
Sister ("Hold Your Hand Out!") Francis
taught in spartan circumstances.
Hanging plants? A class TV?
We never knew such luxury.
Our room was joyless, uninviting:
clanging heat pipes, awful lighting.
Desks were shared by two or three,
supplies were doled out frugally.
The atmosphere in class was tense:
(would Sister Francis now dispense
a warning or a ruler-smack
for whispering behind her back?)
Threatened and intimidated.
That's how I was "educated."
Classrooms now are open, free.
(And often noisy, naturally.)
What a difference! School is cool!
No ruler-smacks, no ridicule.
A place where learning's often fun,
and every student's Number One.
Oh, Sister Francis did her best.
Her sort of teaching worked, I guess.
They didn't know in Sister's time
that school's not prison, youth's no crime.
signature:
(J.D. Evans, a pseudonym, is a New Jersey writer who remembers his
teachers with affection ... occasionally.)

title: No news is front-page stuff for the supermarket tabloids
content:
Did Pope John Paul see UFOs?
Do Brussels sprouts cure cancer?
Did one of Santa's reindeer die?
(Was it Comet? Rudolph? Prancer?)
Can you lose 20 pounds a day
by eating only prunes?
Did Ron and Nancy really go
on separate honeymoons?
Was Jackie O. a prisoner
on Walter Cronkite's yacht?
Can you improve your memory
by munching apricots?
Is Frank Sinatra penniless?
Is Brezhnev really dead?
Can children boost their IQ scores
by eating raisin bread?
Is Princess Di a Russian spy?
Is Henny Youngman Catholic?
Does Cathy Crosby talk to Bing?
Is Bob Hope telepathic?

I made up all those questions,
but who knows? They could be true.
Would anyone believe it, though?
Gee. I don't know.Would you?
signature:
(J.D. Evans, a pseudonym, is a New Jersey writer who reads the front
pages of the Star,The Globe and the National Enquirer at the checkout
counter ... occasionally.)

title: he follies of youth in time go to waist
content:
When I was one and twenty,
I heard a health nut say:
"You better watch your diet
and exercise each day;
Don't smoke, use drugs or alcohol,
you'll pay for every vice."
But I was one and twenty.
Who needed such advice?

When I was six and twenty,
he offered me a grape:
"You're eating too much junk food;
you're getting out of shape.
Play, tennis. Jog. Ride bicycles.
Your lifestyle is a crime."
But I was six and twenty,
and there was lots of time.

When I was five and thirty.
I heard him say again:
"The body is a treasure
that is wasted on most men.
They go to fat too soon,
and too late they see the light."
And in nine days I'll turn 40,
and you know? The guy was right.
signature:
(J.D. Evans, a pseudonym, is a New Jersey writer who resolves to start
exercising ... occasionally.)

title: One man's escargot is another's poison
content:
News item: According to a Gallup poll, the foods
Americans consider least appealing are: snails,
brains, squid and shark.

The snail leaves trails gelatinous:
a gooey, slimy dribble.
The squid has much too many arms
for us to dare a nibble.
The shark's a common murderer,
unwelcome at our table;
and brains are food for cannibals
with appetites unstable.
Exotic names won't fool us
(don't pass the escargots.)
We'll stick with ground up cattle meat:
"Two Whoppers, please.To go."
signature:
(J.D. Evans, a pseudonym, is a New Jersey writer who winces when
people order anchovies on their pizza É occasionally.)

title: For lack of director the news was lost
content:
News item: KYW-TV, the Philadelphia affiliate
of NBC-TV, did not broadcast its 11 o'clock news
program last Sunday night because a director failed
to show up for work.

I fear that I shall never see
the news I missed on channel 3.
The slew of facts and film reports
that told of weather, crime and sports
is lost forever, gone for good,
unaired, unseen, un-understood.

Within my mind now gaps exist:
blank spaces for the news I missed.
(I would not be in such a fix
if I had tuned to 10 or 6.)
Weather forecasts? Hockey scores?
Interviews with senators?
Homicides and burglaries?
Political analyses?
Fires? Crime? Excuse the pun:
I stuck with 3; I witnessed none.
signature:
(J.D. Evans, a pseudonym, is a New Jersey writer who thinks no news is
good news ... occasionally.)

title: "What the ...?" "Heli-Stat."
content:
News item: The General Accounting Office has
concluded that the Heli-Stat, an experimental
aircraft being built in Lakehurst, New Jersey, is too
expensive, way behind schedule and of questionable
value.

The Heli-Stat's a strange machine,
the strangest thing you've ever seen.
It is not pretty lean or sleek.
It's shape is, well, let's say unique.
A big balloon 10 stories high
is filled with gas to make it fly.

Four helicopters then are found
to move the big balloon around.
A giant cage contains it all,
an airborne rota-hover-ball.
A 40-million-dollar craft
that has no fore and has no aft.
It does not fly. At least not yet.
And now the GAO's upset:
They say we don't need Heli-Stats
(those dull and joyless bureaucrats.)
I disagree: I think it's great.
I love that huge and goofy crate.
It symbolizes deficits:
Pour in money, it just sits.
signature:
(J.D. Evans, a pseudonym, is a New Jersey writer who understands why
he pays taxes ... occasionally.)

title: Mother Goose of local news
content:
Localized nursery rhymes. (Any resemblance
to persons living in South Jersey is probably
intentional.)

Little Nicky, Little Nicky, where have you been?
I've been in La Tuna, two-year quarantine.
Little Nicky, Little Nicky, why were you there?
The cops found a derringer under my chair.

Little Mike Morner
sat in a corner and wished it would all go away.
His aides testified
while Mike stayed inside
and said: "I have nothing to say."



Earlie Purlie, pudding and pie
made his city council cry.
He called them names (which wasn't nice.)
A judge told Earl to be polite.

Assemblyperson Muffet
sat on her tuffet
and chewed out The Press. (She was mad.)
"They print what I say,"
she said with dismay.
"And quite often it makes me look bad."

Patrick, Patrick, quite contrary,
how does your garden grow?
With dandelions and eggplants.
The taste? Bravissimo!

Tweedledum and Tweedledee
agreed they'd both retire.
One was chief of all the cops,
the other head of fire.
"It's time to leave," said Tweedledum.


"You're right," said Tweedledee.
"Besides, those hefty pensions
look mighty good to me."

This is the town that dice built.

This is the fog
that covered the town that dice built.

This is the bitterness
that made the fog
that covered the town that dice built.

This is the mistrust
that created the bitterness
that made the fog
that covered the town that dice built.

This is the selfishness
that caused the mistrust
that created the bitterness
that made the fog
that covered the town that dice built.

These are the "leaders"
who played on the selfishness
that caused the mistrust
that created the bitterness
that made the fog
that covered the town that dice built.


These are the people
who elected the "leaders"
who played on the selfishness
that caused the mistrust
that created the bitterness
that made the fog
that covered the town that dice built.

This is the wise man
who saw the people
who elected the "leaders"
who played on the selfishness
that caused the mistrust
that created the bitterness
that made the fog
that covered the town that dice built.

And these are the words
that the wise man said
who saw the people
who elected the "leaders"
who played on the selfishness
that caused the mistrust
that created the bitterness
that made the fog
that covered the town that dice built:
"What did they expect?"
signature:
(J.D. Evans, a pseudonym, is a New Jersey writer who reads Mother
Goose ... occasionally.)

title: He should have phoned his lawyer
content:
Letters published in the Annals of Emergency
Medicine contend that doctors who treated E.T. in
the Steven Spielberg film made so many mistakes
when they tried to resuscitate the creature, they
almost killed him in the process.

"Too much beer and corn chips
threw my systems out of whack.
Blood sugar levels bottomed out
and knocked me on my back.
My skin turned pale and pasty,
my eyes grew small and glazed,
yet all those so-called doctors
missed the symptoms I displayed.
They hooked me up to monitors
to watch my vital signs,
they shocked and poked and probed me.
Such "treatment" is a crime.
I might have died, your honor,
if they had had their way.
And while it's true I didn't,
the law says they should pay.
My suit will show malpractice
led to medical caprices.
For compensation I demand
two tons of Reese's Pieces."
signature:
(J.D. Evans, a pseudonym, is a New Jersey writer who wonders if there
are lawyers in outer space É occasionally.)

title: Aching to be beyond the dental buzz
content:
I wish I could hear waterfalls
or breakers on the beach.
I'd love to hear Niagara howl
or hear a seagull screech.
To hear a child's laughter now
would give my soul a thrill.
I wish I could hear ANYTHING
besides my dentist's drill.

I wish I could see mountain peaks
or rolling fields of grain.
I'd love to see the pyramids
or purple moors in Spain.
I wish I could see nebulae
and quasars out in space.
I wish I could see ANYTHING
besides my dentist's face.

I wish I were in Paris, France,
(or Paris,Tennessee.)
I'd love to be in Holland now
beside the Zuyder Zee.
I wish I could be strolling
down some sunny thoroughfare.
I wish that I were ANYPLACE
but in my dentist's chair.
signature:
(J.D. Evans, a pseudonym, is a New Jersey writer who flosses ...
occasionally.)

title: A lone Ranger glides again in Times' ballet blooper
content:
Correction in the New York Times on Feb. 29:
"Because of a technical error, an incorrect picture
appeared yesterday with an article about the
American Ballet Theater. It showed Mark Morrison,
the Ranger hockey player in place of Mikhail
Baryshnikov, the ballet theater's artistic director."

Mark (Mark) Morrison (Morrison) mastered the tour jete.
He worked on technique and one day last week
tried out for the corps de ballet.

Mark (Mark) Morrison (Morrison) practiced all night and all day:
Port de bras, pas de deux, and adagio, too,
en dedans, entrechat and plie.

Mark (Mark) Morrison (Morrison) had a pathetic debut.
Tragic Mistake Mars Perfect 'Swan Lake'
said the headline above one review.

Mark (M***) Morrison (M*******) wasn't a premier danseur.
He leaped only once.Then stood (like a dunce.)
His skate blades were stuck in the floor.
signature:
(J.D. Evans, a pseudonym, is a New Jersey writer who knows a good
entrechat when he sees one ... occasionally.)

title: TV's anchors, pollsters provoke primary objections
content:
Election Rap:

Caucuses and primaries,
political analyses;
TVs gods, the anchormen,
discuss what's right and wrong with Glenn.
They'll tell us why Maine went for Hart,
and (since we're dumb) they'll use a chart.
The pollsters play their numbers game,
and when they're wrong they make it plain:
It's not their fault, they didn't lie.
A brand new poll will show us why
the labor vote did not appear.
(Another chart will make it clear.)
The field gets narrowed much too soon;
too little "choice" remains in June.
There's too much time and money spent.
These primaries are punishment
for candidates and voters, too.
I think it's time for something new:
A single primary, one election,
a logical (and fair) selection.
A truly nationwide campaign,
one day to vote from Guam to Maine,
in every town in every state.
Let's try it out in '88.
(The anchormen won't like the system.
We'd see 'em less. But I won't miss 'em.)
signature:
(J.D. Evans, a pseudonym, is a New Jersey writer who wonders what

title: he exercising of just excuses
content:
The sun's not up.The streets are dark.
There might be muggers in the park.
(Joggers are choice muggers' prey.)
I do not think I'll run today.

The floor is cold.The bed is warm.
The forecast calls for thunderstorms.
Those clouds look surly, mean and gray.
I do not think I'll run today.

My shoelace broke. My sweatsuit stinks.
I'll just grab forty extra winks.
I overslept? I'm late! Gangway!
I don't have time to run today!

My ankles ache. I hurt my knee.
I'm not sure running's good for me.
I'll start again on Saturday.
No need for me to run today.

Jogging by yourself's a bore.
And getting dressed is such a chore.
It's too much work, too little play.
What good is running anyway?
This shirt seems small.These pants feel tight.
You're right. I ate too much last night.
I look "a little plump," you say?
I think that I shall run today.
signature:
(J.D. Evans, a pseudonym, is a New Jersey writer who runs out of
excuses ... occasionally.)

title: Hallowed be the names of cities
content:
News item: A quarry operation in Clifton, N.J., has
removed most of the cliffs that gave the town its
name in 1867.

How could Clifton lose its cliffs?
Can Vineland lose its vines?
Will Millville one day have no mills?
Will Pinehurst have no pines?
There should be foxes in Fox Hill
(and a ridge in Cedar Ridge.)
The town of Westfield needs a field,
and Bridgeton needs a bridge.

Before you go and name a town
you need to take great care.
It only makes a town look dumb
if its namesake isn't there.
Echo Lake could lose its echo,
Sheep Hill lose its sheep.
And if they start a landfill,
will Deep Hollow stilt be deep?
Eagle Point might lose its birds
(and Eagleswood the same).
You'd think that folks would think ahead
before they picked a name.

(J.D. Evans, a pseudonym, is a New Jersey writer who worries about
place names ... occasionally.)

title: And cement-shoe tap dancers?
content:
News item: The reputed head of organized crime
in Atlantic City has gone into business as an
entertainment promoter.

"I want that you should book this act,"
says the R.H. of O.C.
"I met him once in Texas.
He was doing one-to-three.
A singer? Nah.The guy's OK.
He doesn't name no names.
His act? The guy's a torch man.
He makes things burst in flames.
We build this house on stage, OK?
With furniture and all.
The houselights dim, and he comes in,
then "VAROOOM!" a fireball!
No good? Forget the torch guy.
How 'bout a muscle act?
This guy I got breaks kneecaps
with a wooden baseball bat.
Sounds nasty? Sure it's nasty.
But so's Don Rickles' stuff.
And people pay to see him.
They love that nasty stuff.
Just let the guy audition.
Whatcha got to lose?
This here's a special offer.
It's one you can't refuse."
signature:
(J.D. Evans, a pseudonym, is a New Jersey writer who has been told that
the R.H. of O.C. has a sense of humor ... occasionally.)

title: Extinction is a mere 15 million years away
content:
News item: Scientists have found evidence that
large-scale extinctions of plants and animals occur
on earth every 26 million years. The next mass
extinction could occur in 15 million years.

Darwin's bell will one day ring:
"It's quitting time. For everything!"
Don't send to know for whom it tolls.
It tolls for bats and frogs and moles.
It tolls for gnats and moths and worms,
it tolls for giant pachyderms.
It dings for ducks, it dongs for snails,
it ting-a-lings for humpback whales.
A planet's worth of protoplasm
gone in one swift eco-spasm.
Giant redwoods? Poof! Adieu.
No birds to sing, no cows to moo.
No apple trees, no bighorn sheep.
Gone. All gone, without a peep.
The earth we know may sputter out
in 15 million years (about).
Such prospects make the soul reflective,
and give our world a new perspective.
The End's a cosmic tick away.
Go out and hug a tree today.
signature:
(J.D. Evans, a pseudonym, is a New Jersey writer who tells his maple
tree to keep a stiff upper lip É occasionally.)

title: Rhyming on time can be less than sublime
content:
Thoughts while working on a rhyming commentary
that began with the line: "The CIA is planting mines
to blockade Nicaragua."

Shakespeare had no deadlines.
He didn't scour headlines
seeking sudden inspiration for a weekly work of art.
Wordsworth never worried.
He never rushed or hurried
as he sniffed among the daisies for some truth he could impart.
Poe (though he was stranger)
never felt he was in danger
if he let a month go by without producing any rhyme.

Poets of past ages:
you would strike for higher wages
if you wrote on a computer that was crashing all the time!
Try to write sublimely
on a subject that is timely
once a week and you'd discover that the language is unkind.

Poets in your heavens!
Lend a hand to J.D. Evans.
Seeking rhymes for "Nicaragua" can destroy a poet's mind.

(J.D. Evans, a pseudonym, is a New Jersey writer who places help
wanted ads for a new muse ... occasionally.)

title: With patience (and money) we make princes of frogs
content:
Women who will one day love him,
run to share his warm embraces,
speak his name with dreamy passion,
never saw my son with braces.

Women who will seek his wisdom,
treasure each small word he's said,
never saw the early version
reading comic books in bed.

Women who will say he's charming
(like a prince in fairy tales,)
never tried to watch the Phillies
while he practiced trombone scales.

Women who will sing his praises:
"Strong and gentle, kind and true,"
never saw him punch his brother
when he lost a game of Clue.

Women who will feel their hearts sink
when he passes by their door,
never saw him spill his Hi-C
down his shirt and on the floor.

Women who will sigh and worry,
wondering why they even bother,
never saw him cry for "Dumbo,"
never saw him hug his father.

Women someday will not see him:
awkward, silly, sad, afraid.
Only parents know the secret:
princes are not born, they're made.
signature:
(J.D. Evans, a pseudonym, is a New Jersey writer who used to punch his
sister when he lost at Monopoly ... occasionally.)
